Based on your description and configuration, it could be that the agents are getting similar experiences during training, hindering their ability to learn effectively. The reason why all of them go into the wall could be because the network is not learning from multiple experiences. I have a few suggestions to improve your training:

1. Increase batch_size and buffer_size.
Since you have multiple agents, increasing the `batch_size` and `buffer_size` in your yaml configuration might help improve training. Try increasing them as follows:

```yaml
batch_size: 64
buffer_size: 2048
```

2. Make the food positions more random.
Ensure that food is spawning in different positions for every agent. If the agents are not having diverse experiences, it will be hard for them to learn properly. If the area is the same for all agents, you can try randomizing the initial positions of the agents.

3. Randomize agent starting positions.
As mentioned earlier, randomizing the starting position of the agents can improve their learning. Inside your `CircleController` script, modify the `OnEpisodeBegin` method:

```csharp
public override void OnEpisodeBegin()
{
    // Reset the agent's position
    float randomX = UnityEngine.Random.Range(-areaSize.x / 2, areaSize.x / 2);
    float randomY = UnityEngine.Random.Range(-areaSize.y / 2, areaSize.y / 2);
    transform.localPosition = new Vector3(randomX, randomY, 0);
}
```

4. Add rewards for moving away from the walls.
One reason agents might be getting stuck is that they don't have a clear motivation to avoid the walls. You can add a reward signal inside `OnActionReceived()` method after calculating the new position of the agent but before applying it:

```csharp
public override void OnActionReceived(ActionBuffers actionBuffers)
{
    float moveX = Mathf.Clamp(actionBuffers.ContinuousActions[0], -1, 1);
    float moveY = Mathf.Clamp(actionBuffers.ContinuousActions[1], -1, 1);

    Vector3 newPosition = transform.localPosition + new Vector3(moveX, moveY, 0f) * Time.deltaTime * moveSpeed;

    // Add a reward signal for moving away from the walls
    if (Mathf.Abs(newPosition.x) < areaSize.x / 2 && Mathf.Abs(newPosition.y) < areaSize.y / 2)
    {
        AddReward(0.001f);
    }

    // Update agent position
    transform.localPosition = newPosition;
}
```

Try applying some of these suggestions and monitor changes in the agent's behavior during the learning process. Experiment with different reward signals and positions to create a more diverse learning experience for the agents.

